# Bash begginners guide

# Shell types { sh, bash, csh, tcsh, ksh }.

The file "/etc/shells" gives an overview of known shells on a Linux system.
Your default shell is set in the "/etc/passwd" file.

# buit-in commands
Bourne SHell
{ :, ., break, cd, continue, eval, exec, exit, export, getopts, hash, pwd, readonly,
return, set, shift, test, [, times, trap, umask, unset }

Bash
{ alias, bind, builtin, command, declare, echo, enable, help, let, local, logout, printf,
read, shopt, type, typeset, ulimit, unalias }

# Shell Commands
-> touch file1 file2
-> ls | more
-> declare ( shell parameters )

# Debug the shell script
set -x                  # activate debugging from here
w
set +x                  # stop debugging from here


